class="headline_area"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/hardware/linux-install-nicstat-command-to-print-network-statistics-for-nics/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent link to Solaris / Linux: nicstat Command Show Network Interface Card Statistics">Solaris / Linux: nicstat Command Show Network Interface Card Statistics</a></h2><p
class="headline_meta">by <span
class="author vcard"><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/tips/about-us" rel="author" class="url fn">nixCraft</a></span> on <abbr
class="published" title="2013-03-10">March 10, 2013</abbr> &middot; <span><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/hardware/linux-install-nicstat-command-to-print-network-statistics-for-nics/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span
class="dsq-postid" rel="348 http://www.cyberciti.biz/?p=348">0 comments</span></a></span></p><p
class="headline_meta">in <span><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/open-source/command-line-hacks/" title="View all posts in Command Line Hacks" rel="category tag">Command Line Hacks</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/hardware/" title="View all posts in Hardware" rel="category tag">Hardware</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/networking/" title="View all posts in Networking" rel="category tag">Networking</a></span></p></div><div
class="format_text entry-content"><p><img
src="http://s0.cyberciti.org/uploads/cms/2013/03/nicstat-welcome-150x150.png" alt="nicstat-welcome" width="150" height="150" class="alignright size-full wp-image-353" /><span
class="drop_cap">T</span>he nicstat command is top like utility for network interface card (NIC). It displays information and statistics about all your network card such as packets, kilobytes per second, average packet sizes and more. It works under Solaris and Linux operating systems. <br/><br/></p><p>In this post, I will explain how to install and use the nicstat command to find out stats about your NICs under Debian / Ubuntu / RHEL / CentOS Linux operating systems.</p><p
