class="headline_area"><h2 class="entry-title"><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/hardware/linux-find-and-recover-wasted-disk-space/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent link to agedu: Unix / Linux Command For Tracking Down Wasted Disk Space">agedu: Unix / Linux Command For Tracking Down Wasted Disk Space</a></h2><p
class="headline_meta">by <span
class="author vcard"><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/tips/about-us" rel="author" class="url fn">nixCraft</a></span> on <abbr
class="published" title="2012-10-20">October 20, 2012</abbr> &middot; <span><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/hardware/linux-find-and-recover-wasted-disk-space/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span
class="dsq-postid" rel="245 http://www.cyberciti.biz/?p=245">10 comments</span></a></span></p><p
class="headline_meta">in <span><a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/open-source/command-line-hacks/" title="View all posts in Command Line Hacks" rel="category tag">Command Line Hacks</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/hardware/" title="View all posts in Hardware" rel="category tag">Hardware</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/howto/" title="View all posts in Howto" rel="category tag">Howto</a>, <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/topics/storage/" title="View all posts in Storage" rel="category tag">Storage</a></span></p></div><div
class="format_text entry-content"><p><span
class="drop_cap">M</span>ost sysadmin will run low on disk space. Users will demand more space and you need to free space. You will find out files that&#8217;s a waste of space and delete it or <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/faq/linux-tape-backup-with-mt-and-tar-command-howto/">move to an archive medium</a>. But, how do you find the right files to delete that can help recover maximum space? Say hello to <kbd>agedu</kbd> tool (pronounced as &#8216;age dee you&#8217;) &#8211; it scans a directory tree and produces reports about how much disk space is used in each directory and subdirectory, and also how that usage of disk space corresponds to files with last-access times a long time ago. In other words, this command might help you to free up disk space.</p><p
class="to_comments"><span
class="bracket">{</span> <a
href="http://www.cyberciti.biz/hardware/linux-find-and-recover-wasted-disk-space/#comments" rel="nofollow"><span>10</span> comments</a> <span
class="bracket">}</span></p></div></div><div
